40|$|China's {{international}} investment {{position is}} characterized by large net foreign assets, a dominance of low-return foreign exchange reserves and costly foreign <b>direct</b> <b>investment</b> in foreign <b>assets</b> and foreign liabilities. In addition, China's foreign investment positions are facing potentially large exchange risks. These features reflect entrenched institutional and structural problems in China, including underdeveloped capital markets, biased resource allocation and a defective social security system. China's net creditor status might actually be an indication of weakness rather than strength. To improve its {{international investment position}}, China must speed up economic reforms and allow the market to play {{a fundamental role in}} resource allocation. Copyright 2007 Institute of World Economics and Politics, Chinese Academy of Social Sciences. ...|$|R
