40|$|This paper {{summarizes}} recent arguments/findings on {{two aspects}} of foreign <b>direct</b> <b>investment</b> (FDI) : its correlation with economic growth and its determinants. The first part focuses on recent literature regarding positive spillovers from FDI while the second deals with the determinants of FDI. The paper finds that while substantial support exists for positive spillovers from FDI, {{there is no consensus}} on causality. On determinants, the paper finds that market size, infrastructure quality, political/economic stability, and free trade zones are important for FDI, while results are mixed regarding the importance of fiscal incentives, the business/investment climate, labor costs, and openness. Foreign direct investment;Economic growth;fdi, <b>direct</b> <b>investment,</b> foreign investment, foreign investors, investors, market size, host country, fdis, investment climate, technology transfer, foreign capital, host economy, <b>direct</b> foreign <b>investment,</b> joint ventures, multinational firms, domestic investment, tax incentives, corporate tax rates, corporate tax, foreign ownership, international investment, market access, export processing zones, industrial development, foreign affiliates, foreign technology, market failure, host developing countries, tax system, host investment climate, macroeconomic stability, manufacturing sector, host-country, multinational enterprises, <b>investment</b> decisions, manufacturing <b>direct</b> foreign <b>investment,</b> foreign investments, investment barriers, foreign investor, international trade, foreign trade, investment regime, import substitution, industrial economies, knowledge diffusion, foreign car, domestic fixed <b>investment,</b> <b>direct</b> foreign <b>investments,</b> multinational enterprise, foreign investment advisory service, investment location decisions, foreign market, expropriation, private foreign investment, fixed investment, local capital markets, foreign markets, inve